[edited]
<http://www.doh.gov.uk/cjd/stats/may02.htm>

Monthly Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease Statistics; Tue 7 May 2002
-----------------------------------------------------------
The Department of Health issued on Tue 7 May 2002 the latest information
about the numbers of known cases of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease. This
includes cases of variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease [abbreviated in
ProMED-mail as (vCJD) or CJD (new var.)] -- the form of the disease thought
to be linked to bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE). The position is as
follows:
Definite and probable CJD cases in the UK:
Year/ Referrals/ Sporadic/ Iatrogenic/ Familial/ GSS/ vCJD/ Total deaths
1990/ 53/ 28/ 5/ 0/ 0/ -/ 33
1991/ 75/ 32/ 1/ 3/ 0/ -/ 36
1992/ 96/ 44/ 2/ 5/ 1/ -/ 52
1993/ 78/ 38/ 4/ 2/ 2/ -/ 46
1994/ 116/ 51/ 1/ 4/ 3/ -/ 59
1995/ 87/ 35/ 4/ 2/ 3/ 3/ 47
1996/ 134/ 40/ 4/ 2/ 4/ 10/ 60
1997/ 161/ 59/ 6/ 4/ 1/ 10/ 80
1998/ 154/ 63/ 3/ 4/ 1/ 18/ 89
1999/ 169/ 61/ 6/ 2/ 0/ 15 /84
2000/ 178/ 48/ 1/ 2/ 1/ 28/ 80
2001/ 172/ 50/ 3/ 2/ 2/ 20/ 77
2002*/ 42/ 6/ 0/ 1/ 0/ 7/ 14
*As of 6 May 2002
Summary of vCJD cases
Deaths:
Deaths from definite vCJD (confirmed): 89
Deaths from probable vCJD (without neuropathological confirmation): 18
Deaths from probable vCJD (neuropathological confirmation pending): 4
Number of deaths from definite or probable vCJD (as above): 111
Alive:
Number of probable vCJD cases still alive: 10
Total number of definite or probable vCJD (dead and alive): 121
The precise definitions of the terms: Referrals, Deaths, Definite cases,
Probable vCJD cases, Sporadic, Probable sporadic, Iatrogenic, Familial,
GSS, variant CJD, and the case definitions can be found by accessing the
Department of Health web-site or by reference to the preceding ProMED-mail
post in this thread [CJD (new var.) - UK: update Mar 2002 20020305.3693].
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Since the previous monthly statistics released by the Department of Health
on Mon 2 Apr 2002, the total number of definite or probable vCJD cases has
increased by a single confirmed vCJD case and 3 probable vCJD cases still
alive. In view of the long incubation period of vCJD, it is still too early
to predict the future trend. The figures suggest neither an imminent
dramatic rise in the number of vCJD cases nor a decline. - Mod.CP]
